<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-06-03T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-06-03T09:00:00-05:00" n="820" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d820">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">867.4016/517: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-06-03T16:00:00+02:00"><hi rend="italic">June 3,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 4:55
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>75. The Minister for Foreign Affairs asked me to telegraph Department:
                            “Greek Government earnestly hopes for American participation on
                            commissions to investigate Asia Minor atrocities.”</p>
                        <p>[Paraphrase.] It is my opinion that the Greek Government is very anxious
                            to have the United States participate but that the Minister for Foreign
                            Affairs is not very hopeful that the Department will act on his request.
                            [End paraphrase.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>